Analysis of English Football Success Stories

Rohit Sengupta

Introduction and Background:

English football is not just a sport; it's a cultural phenomenon, deeply woven into the fabric of the nation. From the bustling streets of London to the serene landscapes of the North, the game resonates with a passion and fervor that few other sports can claim. This is a country where football has been played since medieval times, evolving over centuries from chaotic village games to the structured competitions we see today. The Premier League stands as the pinnacle of this evolution. Although the Premier League was founded in 1992, many clubs which make it and many other leagues up are filled with histories that stretch back over a century. Clubs like Manchester United, Liverpool, and Arsenal are not just names; they represent legacies, memories, and an enduring spirit that has captivated fans globally.

But what truly sets English football apart is its unique blend of tradition and innovation. The terraced houses surrounding stadiums, the age-old rivalries, the songs that have been passed down through generations all these coexist with cutting-edge stadiums, international fanbases connected through digital mediums, and a cosmopolitan roster of players and managers from every corner of the globe. Football in the UK has always been more than 90 minutes on the pitch. It's about community and identity. It's about the highs of last-minute winners and the lows of heartbreaking relegations. It's about the stories of underdogs defying the odds and giants being toppled. It's an ongoing narrative that shapes weekends and defines moods, with every fan and player penning their own chapter.

The importance of football in England cannot be understated. Not only does it drive the economy with its global viewership and merchandise sales, but it also plays a vital role in the nation's social and cultural landscape. The game has given a voice to communities, provided moments of collective joy and sorrow, and continues to be a source of hope and inspiration for many.

In the chapters that follow, we delve into three distinct narratives from English football, each highlighting a different pathway to success, each emphasizing the unpredictability, charm, and sheer beauty of the beautiful game in the heart of England.

Brentford's Moneyball Approach

At its core, Brentford's 'Moneyball' strategy represented a significant shift in how football clubs approached player acquisition and valuation. In a world where clubs often splurged astronomical sums on big-name players, Brentford's reliance on data analytics to identify undervalued talent was both novel and bold. By focusing on metrics that often went unnoticed in traditional scouting, they were able to field a competitive team at a fraction of the cost of their rivals. Their success with this model provided a tangible case study for the efficacy of a data-driven approach in football.

The impact of this strategy has been far-reaching. Not only did it cement Brentford's reputation as an innovative club, but it also spurred a wider appreciation for analytics in football. Clubs across tiers started investing more in data departments, realizing the potential of analytics in leveling the playing field. More info can be learned in this insightful video below: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mrwwVoD1RQQ

Analyzing Brentford's journey gives insights into how football clubs can operate efficiently in an increasingly inflated market. Understanding the metrics they prioritized and their decision-making processes can serve as a roadmap for other clubs with limited resources, offering an alternative to the conventional wisdom that financial might is the primary route to success.

Manchester City's Financial Transformation

The tale of Manchester City post-2008 is one of rapid ascent, underpinned by unprecedented financial investment. The influx of wealth from the Abu Dhabi United Group transformed a historically underachieving club into one of the world's most dominant footballing forces. Their investment wasn't just limited to acquiring top-tier talent; it extended to revamping infrastructure, scouting networks, and youth development.

City's transformation had a cascading effect on global football. The elevated spending raised the stakes in the Premier League, forcing other clubs to adapt, whether by seeking their own wealthy investors or innovating in other areas. The English top tier became even more competitive, attracting elite talent and amplifying its global appeal. More can be learned here: https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2670212-the-remarkable-story-of-manchester-citys-rise-under-sheikh-mansour

Data analysis of City's transformation provides a deep understanding of how financial muscle, when applied strategically, can expedite success. By analyzing their spending patterns, squad building, and return on investment, one can derive lessons on effective resource allocation and strategic planning in football.

Leicester City's Fairytale Championship

The 2015-16 Premier League season stands as a testament to the unpredictable beauty of football. Leicester City's triumph, in the face of 5000-1 odds, was a stunning reminder that passion, teamwork, and tactical nous could still trump financial might. With a squad built on a shoestring budget compared to the league's giants, the Foxes defied logic and expectation.

This underdog story reinvigorated a belief in the magic of football, proving that with the right management, scouting, and team spirit, anything was possible. Clubs and fans worldwide took inspiration, realizing that with astute planning and cohesion, they too could overcome seemingly insurmountable odds. These two videos are definitely my favorites on the matter and provide a view of what it was like: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SkfTShRBJ68 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gTbxrPQLxEo&t=157s

A data-driven analysis of Leicester's season helps dissect the elements that contributed to their success. From player performance metrics to tactical adjustments, understanding the data behind their championship run offers a blueprint for maximizing output from limited resources. It emphasizes the importance of team dynamics, the value of underrated talent, and the potential outcomes when all the pieces come together harmoniously.

In this tutorial section, we delve into cleaning and preparing our dataset related to transfer activities in the English Football League (EFL) between 2012 and 2021. Proper data cleaning is essential for accurate analysis, especially when dealing with monetary values, which often come in various formats.

First, we ensure that the 'year' column values are numerical. This is crucial for filtering data in subsequent steps.

We then filter our dataset to consider only the records within the relevant timeframe, i.e., from 2012 to the end of 2020.

Transfer fees in football can be complex, with values sometimes being undisclosed, loans, or free transfers. We address these intricacies by:

Converting all fees to strings. Defining a list of non-numeric values that need replacement. Cleaning the fee column by setting non-numeric values to zero.

The data might have transfer fees represented in various ways, such as millions (e.g., "2.5m") or thousands (e.g., "500Th."). We need to convert these values into a consistent numerical format for effective analysis.

Using regular expressions, we recognize these patterns and perform the necessary conversions.

By the end of this process, we have a clean, consistent dataset with transfer records from 2012 to 2020, with all transfer fees in a standardized numerical format, ready for any downstream analysis.

In[]:
transfers_efl['year'] = pd.to_numeric(transfers_efl['year'], errors='coerce')

# Filter rows within the relevant timeframe (2012 to 2021)
transfers_efl = transfers_efl[(transfers_efl['year'] >= 2012) & (transfers_efl['year'] < 2021)]

transfers_efl['fee'] = transfers_efl['fee'].astype(str)

# Replace non-numeric values with zeros
non_numeric_values = ['?', '-', 'loan transfer', 'free transfer']

def clean_fee(value):
    if value in non_numeric_values or re.match(r'^End of loan', value):
        return 0
    return value

transfers_efl['fee'] = transfers_efl['fee'].apply(clean_fee)

# Convert monetary values to numerical form
def convert_monetary_value(value):
    if isinstance(value, str) and re.match(r'^', value):
        if re.match(r'^\d+\.\d+m$', value):
            return int(float(value[1:-1]) * 1000000)
        elif re.match(r'^\d+Th\.$', value):
            return int(float(value[1:-3]) * 1000)
    if isinstance(value, str) and re.match(r'^Loan fee:', value):
        if re.match(r'^Loan fee:\d+\.\d+m$', value):
            return int(float(value[10:-1]) * 1000000)
        elif re.match(r'^Loan fee:\d+Th\.$', value):
            return int(float(value[10:-3]) * 1000)
    return value

transfers_efl['fee'] = transfers_efl['fee'].apply(convert_monetary_value)
